<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Learn DSA</title>
    <link rel='stylesheet' href='/stylesheets/style.css' />
    <%- include('../../partials/head') %>
  </head>
  <body>

    <div class="d-flex">
      <%- include('../../partials/sidebar') %>

      <main class="flex-fill p-4">
        <div class="text-center">
          <h3>Post-Order Traversal</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Post-Order Traversal — Introduction

            Post-order traversal is a depth-first traversal technique for trees.

            In this method, we visit nodes in the following order:

            1. Left subtree
            2. Right subtree
            3. Root node

            ####Order = Left → Right → Root####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
              C-->F;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Step-by-Step Process

            To perform post-order traversal:

            1. Traverse the left subtree recursively
            2. Traverse the right subtree recursively
            3. Visit the current node

            This ensures children are processed before their parent.

            ####T(n) = T(left) + T(right) + 1####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Example Traversal

            Given this tree:

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
              C-->F;
            /mermaid

            Post-order traversal sequence:

            D → E → B → F → C → A

            ####Result = [D, E, B, F, C, A]####
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Recursive Implementation

            Post-order traversal is naturally implemented using recursion:

            - Call function on left child
            - Call function on right child
            - Process the node

            ####visit(node) after children####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              Start-->Left;
              Left-->Right;
              Right-->Visit;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Use Cases

            Post-order traversal is useful when:

            - Deleting a tree (children before parent)
            - Evaluating expression trees
            - Calculating subtree properties

            ####Useful for bottom-up computation####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              Leaves-->Parent;
              Parent-->Root;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <!-- CONTROLS --> 
        <div class="nav-controls"> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark me-2" id="prev">← Prev</button> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark" id="next">Next →</button> 
        </div> 
        <div class="progress-container"> 
          <div class="progress-bar" id="progress"></div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide-counter"> 
          <span id="current">1</span>/<span id="total">1</span> 
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </body>
  <script src="/javascripts/render-slides.js"></script>
</html>
